# Memory changes must be validated with the bench

## CRITICAL INVARIANT — memory logic lives in the API, NEVER in the bench

**Read this before touching anything under `apps/api/bench/`.**

- ALL memory logic — extraction, retrieval, ranking, recall, embedding, prompt
  formatting — lives in `apps/api/src/memory/**`. That is the code PROD runs.
- The bench harness (`apps/api/bench/**`) contains **NO memory logic**. It ONLY
  imports the production memory functions and replicates how PROD assembles
  them. It is a measurement instrument, not a second implementation.
- **NEVER add a retrieval/recall/embedding/formatting path to the bench that
  production does not run.** If a capability would help the bench, it must be
  added to `apps/api/src/memory/**` AND used by the production pipeline FIRST;
  the bench then imports it. No exceptions, no "bench-only" lanes.
- If you catch yourself writing retrieval/embedding/formatting/recall code under
  `apps/api/bench/`, STOP — move it to `apps/api/src/memory/` and import it.
- The bench's ENTIRE value is faithfully measuring prod. A path that exists only
  in the bench makes the score a lie. Tuning the bench to move a number without
  the same change in prod is the cardinal sin here.
- The only bench-local concern is the harness scaffolding: corpus loading,
  timeline replay, the constrained answerer/judge instrument, scoring math,
  artifacts. None of that is memory logic.

You're editing a path that can move Aura's memory quality. These changes are
**not falsifiable by typecheck alone** — validate with the memory bench. Read
the `aura-memory-bench` skill for the full workflow.

The bench replays each corpus on a **production-faithful timeline**: per
assistant-reply (`exchange`) extraction runs as a producer that advances a global
watermark, and each question is scored the moment the watermark passes its
timestamp, retrieving **bi-temporally as-of that instant** (no future leak). It
defaults to `--dataset=lme` (real question timestamps); LoCoMo/toy fall back to
end-of-conversation. The full model is in the `aura-memory-bench` skill +
`apps/api/bench/src/timeline.ts`.

The bench runs **in CI on PRs** that touch memory paths. The action runs the
medium LongMemEval (`--dataset=lme --replay=exchange`) pass on an isolated Neon
branch, posts a sticky PR comment with per-category deltas vs the target branch,
and **commits the regenerated `apps/api/bench/history.jsonl` +
`apps/api/bench/README.md` + root `README.md` snapshot back to the PR branch**
(pushed with `GITHUB_TOKEN`, so it doesn't retrigger CI). You don't paste numbers
by hand or run medium/full yourself — CI produces the authoritative numbers on
the PR.

The timeline + as-of model and `exchange` default reset the baseline once: expect
a one-time `history.jsonl` delta (notably `temporal` / `knowledge_update`) on the
first run after it lands. Expected, not a regression.

Locally is the fast iteration loop while you're developing the change: run the
cheap subsets to sanity-check before you push, then let CI handle the medium run.

**Cursor Cloud Agents: use the mid-size local loop.** Toy is too small to see
real failure modes; medium is too slow (~2h) to iterate on. A Cloud Agent has
`DATABASE_URL` + AI keys in its env, so it can run a **mid-size pass
(`--dataset=lme --limit=10` ≈ 60 Qs, ~10–30 min) against its own Neon DB in a
persistent `--bench-id` workspace, then `bench:inspect --triage`/`--case` and
query the stored memories directly** to find the actual failure cause and
iterate — the thing CI can't give you (CI wipes its workspace). See the
`aura-bench-local-iteration` skill for the exact loop (run → triage → inspect DB
→ iterate → clean up).

## Runtime + cost dictate HOW you run it

| Run | Command | Time | Cost | Who runs it |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Smoke | `pnpm bench:memory --dataset=toy --log` | ~1 min | cents | **You** (background) |
| Iteration | `pnpm bench:memory --dataset=lme --subset=fast --log` | a few min | ~$2 | **You** (background) |
| Standard | `pnpm bench:memory --dataset=lme --subset=medium --log` | ~1 hour (~330 Qs) | ~$10 | **CI on the PR** (don't run locally) |
| Full | `pnpm bench:memory --dataset=lme --subset=full --log` | ~2–3 hours (2,486 Qs) | real money | **Ask the user** (manual dispatch) |

## Rules for invoking it

- **NEVER block the shell on a bench run.** Do not pipe it through `tail`,
  `head`, or `tee` in a foreground call — a full run can take an hour and will
  hang your turn. Cheap runs you launch yourself MUST be fire-and-forget:
  start them with `block_until_ms: 0` and let the completion notification tell
  you when they're done.
- **Smoke / fast subsets only**: you may run these yourself (background) to
  sanity-check a change before handing off.
- **Medium / full runs cost real money and take a long time**: do NOT run them
  autonomously. Give the user the exact command and ask them to run it, then
  commit the regenerated `history.jsonl` + READMEs.
- Always pass `--log --note="<what changed>"` so the result is recorded.
- Iterate narrow first: `--category=<axis> --limit=3` before widening (see skill).

## Investigating failures (don't hand-roll repro scripts)

After (or during) a run, use `pnpm bench:inspect` instead of writing throwaway
DB scripts — it reads the run's artifacts under `apps/api/bench/runs/<id>/`:

- `pnpm bench:inspect` — newest run's per-category QA+recall tally + failure list (pure file read).
- `pnpm bench:inspect --triage` — buckets each failure as `no-evidence-extracted` / `evidence-hidden-by-as-of` / `visible-but-failed` (extraction vs retrieval vs downstream).
- `pnpm bench:inspect --case=<id>` — one case: the literal memory block the answerer saw + each evidence memory's visibility/retrieved flags.

`--triage`/`--case` query the run's `bench-<runId>` workspace, which is **wiped
on a clean finish** — interrupt the run (Ctrl-C, it saves partial results) if you
want to inspect memories. Full workflow + the recurring root causes are in the
`aura-memory-bench` skill.

## Reuse expensive stages instead of re-ingesting

A default medium/full run re-ingests and re-extracts everything (>70 min) into a
throwaway workspace. For repeated runs, pin a persistent workspace and reuse the
expensive stages (full details + invalidation rules in the `aura-memory-bench` skill):

- Seed once: `--dataset=lme --subset=medium --bench-id=<key> --log`.
- Retrieval/answer-only iteration: `--bench-id=<key> --from=score` (reuses messages + memories; the watermark starts at +inf so every question is immediately releasable against the final pool).
- After an extraction or schema change: `--bench-id=<key> --from=extract` (reuses messages, re-extracts).

## "Δ vs prior" only compares like-for-like

Deltas compare against the newest prior run with the **same corpus hash and the
exact same sampled case set** (`caseSetHash` in `bench/src/score.ts`). A `fast`
(n≈4) run will NOT diff against a `medium` (n≈30) baseline — the case sets
differ — so it shows `—` instead of a fake regression. For a real before/after,
run with the **same subset/corpus** as the baseline you're comparing to.

The CI PR comment applies the same like-for-like rule, but its baseline is the
**target branch's committed `history.jsonl`** (read git-natively, not from the
ephemeral run DB) — see `bench/src/pr-delta.ts` and `bench/scripts/pr-comment.ts`.
When there's no comparable base entry it shows absolute scores, not a fake delta.
